Report on the Audit of the Financial Statements
Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit
We have performed audits of the accompanying financial statements of 3M Employee Retirement Income
Plan,anemployee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA),
as permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) (ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit). The financial
statements comprise the statements of net assets available for benefits as of December 31, 2024 and
2023, the related statement of changes in net assets available for benefits for the years then ended, the
statement of accumulated plan benefits as of December 31, 2023, andtherelatedstatement of changes
in accumulated plan benefits for the year then ended, and the related notes to the financial statements.
Management, having determined it is permissible in the circumstances, has elected to have the audits of
3M Employee Retirement Income Plan's financial statements performed in accordance with ERISA
Section 103(a)(3)(C) pursuant to 29 CFR 2520.103-8 of the Department of Labor's Rules and
Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA. As permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C),
our audits need not extend to any statements or information related to assets held for investment of the
plan (investment information) by a bank or similar institution or insurance carrier that is regulated,
supervised, and subject to periodic examination by a state or federal agency, provided that the
statements or information regarding assets so held are prepared and certified to by the bank or similar
institution or insurance carrier in accordance with 29 CFR 2520.103-5of the Department of Labor's Rules
and Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA (qualified institution).
Management has obtained certifications from qualified institutions as of December 31, 2024 and 2023,
and for the years then ended, stating that the certified investment information, as described in Note 3 to
the financial statements, are complete and accurate.

Basis for Opinion
We conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted in the United States
of America (GAAS). Our responsibilities under those standards are further described in the Auditors’
Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements section of our report. We are required to be
independent of 3M Employee Retirement Income Plan and to meet our other ethical responsibilities in
accordance with the relevant ethical requirements relating to our audits. We believe that the audit
evidence we have obtained is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for our ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C) audit opinion.
Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and for the
design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair
presentation of financial statements that are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or
error. Management's election of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audits does not affect management's
responsibility for the financial statements.
In preparing the financial statements, management is required to evaluate whether there are conditions
or events, considered in the aggregate, that raise substantial doubt about 3M Employee Retirement
Income Plan's ability to continue as a going concern for one year after the date that the financial
statements are available to be issued.
Management is also responsible for maintaining current plan instruments, including all plan amendments,
administering the plans, and determining that the plan's transactions that are presented and disclosed in
the financial statements are in conformity with the plan's provisions, including maintaining sufficient
records with respect to each of the participants, to determine the benefits due or which may become due
to such participants.
Auditors’ Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements
Except as described in the Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit section of our
report, our objectives are to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements as a
whole are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud orerror, and to issue an auditors’report
that includes our opinion. Reasonable assurance is a high level of assurance but is not absolute
assurance and therefore is not a guarantee that an audit conducted in accordance with GAAS will always
detect a material misstatement when it exists. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting
from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional
omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control. Misstatements are considered material
ifthere is a substantial likelihood that, individually or in the aggregate, they would influence the judgment
made by a reasonable user based on the financial statements.
In performing an audit in accordance with GAAS, we:
 Exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audit.
 Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to
fraud or error, and design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks. Such
procedures include examining, on a test basis, evidence regarding the amounts and disclosures
in the financial statements.

December 31, 2024 and 2023
Note 1 - Plan Description
The following description of 3M Employee Retirement Income Plan (the "Plan") provides only general
information. Participants should refer to the plan agreement for a more complete description of the Plan's
provisions.
General
The Plan is a noncontributory defined benefit plan covering substantially all United States regular full-time
and part-time employees of 3M Company and its subsidiaries (the "Company" or "3M") hired prior to
January 1, 2009. The Plan is subject to the provisions of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of
1974 ("ERISA").
In January 2024, the Company announced that the Plan will freeze U.S. defined benefit pension benefits
for non-U.S. employees effective December 31, 2028.
Effective April 1, 2024, 3M spun off its health care business and Solventum Corporation, a company
independent from 3M, was formed. Pursuant to this spin-off, the Solventum Employee Retirement Income
Plan was also formed effective April 1, 2024. Approximately $1,827,000,000 of the Plan's actuarial
present value of accumulated plan benefits and approximately $1,839,000,000 of the Plan's assets were
then transferred out of the Plan and into the Solventum Employee Retirement Income Plan.
In June 2024, the Company purchased a group annuity contract from Metropolitan Tower Life Insurance
Company and transferred approximately $2,300,000,000 of the Plan's actuarial present value of
accumulated plan benefits and related plan assets.
Eligibility and Benefits
The Plan consists of Portfolio I and Portfolio II. Employees who have completed three years or more of
credited service or have reached age 65 are entitled to annual pension benefits beginning at normal
retirement age (65). Benefits are subject to certain maximum limits as defined in the Plan and adjustment
for various options on forms of payment. The Plan allows for early retirement beginning at age 55,
assuming certain requirements are met. If participants terminate employment before completing three
years of service, they forfeit the right to receive benefits under the Plan.
Portfolio I is closed to new U.S. participants effective January 1, 2001, and to new 3M Puerto Rico
employees effective January 1, 2004. Employees of 3M or a 3M U.S. subsidiary participating in the Plan
who became participants in this Plan before January 1, 2001 and who did not elect to transfer to Portfolio
II will continue to participate in this Plan so long as they remain employed by 3M or another participating
subsidiary as a salaried or hourly non-union production/maintenance/warehouse employee. Employees
of 3M Puerto Rico who became participants in this Plan prior to January 1, 2004, will continue to
participate in this Plan as long as they remain employed by 3M Puerto Rico.
Portfolio II is closed to new U.S. participants effective January 1, 2009. Employees are eligible to
participate in the Plan if they are an active regular U.S. or Puerto Rico salaried or hourly non-union
production/maintenance/warehouse employee of 3M or a participating subsidiary of 3M that offers the
Plan and were either hired by 3M U.S. before January 1, 2001 and elected to transfer to Portfolio II, if
they were hired after January 1, 2001 (January 1, 2004 if 3M Puerto Rico) and before January 1, 2009, or
if they were participants in certain other pension plans that have merged into the Plan over time.
The Portfolio I benefit provides an annuity based upon a formula that considers age, pension service,
pension earnings and a Social Security breakpoint. The Portfolio II benefit also provides an annuity based
upon a formula that considers age, pension service and pension earnings, but that utilizes a Social
Security integration level rather than a Social Security breakpoint.

Note 1 - Plan Description (Continued)
The Plan also offers a lump-sum payment option for participants. The lump-sum payment for participants
in Portfolio I will be the actuarial equivalent present value of the participant’s benefit payable at age 65 in
the form of a single life annuity. If the Portfolio I participant qualifies for the supplemental 3M Social
Security bridge benefit, it will be included in the calculation of the lump-sum payment. The lump-sum
payment for the Portfolio II participants will be equal to the greater of the participant’s total pension value
at the time they leave 3M, increased by 4 percent per year until the earlier of (1) the date participant’s
pension begins, or (2) the date the participant reaches age 65, or the actuarial equivalent present value of
the participant’s future benefit payments.
Contributions
Contributions to the Plan are determined using the projected unit credit actuarial cost method. 3M's
funding policy is to make annual payments to the Plan in amounts necessary to ensure that employee
benefits will be fully provided for by the time participants retire.
The yield on investments (interest, dividends and net realized and unrealized gains and losses on
investments) serves to reduce future contributions that would otherwise be required to provide for the
defined level of benefits. The funding is designed to maintain assets near the full funding limit.
The Plan met the ERISA minimum funding requirements for 2024 and 2023. Therefore, no contributions
were required to be made to the Plan in 2024 or 2023.
401(h) Account
In addition to the normal retirement benefits, the Plan includes a medical-benefit component to fund a
portion of the postretirement obligation for retirees and their beneficiaries under the 3M Retiree Welfare
Benefit Plan in accordance with Section 401(h) of the Internal Revenue Code ("IRC"). A separate account
has been established and maintained in the Plan for the net assets related to the medical-benefit
component (the "401(h) account"). The related obligations for health benefits are not included in this
Plan’s obligations in the statements of accumulated plan benefits but are reflected as obligations in the
financial statements of the related 3M Retiree Welfare Benefit Plan. The net assets of the 401(h) account
includes investments, as well as receivables and payables.
In accordance with IRC Section 401(h), the Plan’s investments in the 401(h) account may not be used
for, or diverted to, any purpose other than providing health benefits for retirees and their beneficiaries.
Any assets transferred to the 401(h) account from the Plan in a qualified transfer of excess pension plan
assets (and any income allocable thereto) that are not used during the plan year must be transferred out
of the 401(h) account back to the Plan.
Plan participants do not contribute to the 401(h) account. Employer contributions or qualified transfers to
the 401(h) account are determined annually and are at the discretion of 3M.
Trustee
The Bank of New York Mellon/BNY Mellon N.A. (the "Trustee") is the trustee of the Plan.

Note 2 - Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)
Investment Valuation and Income Recognition
Investments held by the Plan are stated at fair value (see Note 4), except for an insurance contract. The
insurance contract is an Immediate Participation Guarantee ("IPG") contract with MN Life Insurance
Company and is valued at contract value. Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell
an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the
measurement date.
Purchases and sales of securities are recorded on a trade-date basis. Interest income is recorded as
earned. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date.
Benefit Payments
Benefits are recorded when paid.
Administrative Costs
3M pays certain internal administrative costs of the Plan. External administrative costs, including trustee
fees and investment management expenses, are paid by the Plan.
Actuarial Present Value of Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits are those future periodic payments that are attributable, under the Plan’s
provisions, to the service that employees have rendered. Accumulated plan benefits include benefits
expected to be paid to (a) retired or terminated employees or their beneficiaries, (b) beneficiaries of
employees who have died, and (c) present employees or their beneficiaries.
The present value of accumulated plan benefits is actuarially determined and is the amount that results
from applying actuarial assumptions to adjust the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time value of
money (through discounts for interest) and the probability of payment due to death, disability, or
retirement between the valuation date and the expected date of payment.

Risks and Uncertainties
Contributions to the Plan and the accumulated plan benefits are reported based on certain assumptions
pertaining to interest rates, inflation rates, and employee demographics. Due to the changing nature of
these assumptions, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in these assumptions will occur in the
near term and, due to the uncertainties inherent in setting assumptions, that the effect of such changes
could be material to the financial statements. Investment securities are exposed to various risks, such as
interest rate, market, and credit risks. It is at least reasonably possible that changes in the values of
investment securities will occur in the near term and that such changes could materially affect the
financial statements.
Use of Estimates
The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the
United States of America requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the
reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of
the financial statements and the reported amounts of additions and deductions during the reporting
period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.
Subsequent Events
The financial statements and related disclosures include evaluation of events up through and including
October 14, 2025, which is the date the financial statements were available to be issued.

Note 4 - Fair Value Measurements
Accounting standards require certain assets and liabilities be reported at fair value in the financial
statements and provide a framework for establishing that fair value. The framework for determining fair
value is based on a hierarchy that prioritizes the valuation techniques and inputs used to measure fair
value.
Level 1
Fair values determined by Level 1 inputs use quoted prices in active markets for identical assets that the
Plan has the ability to access.
Level 2
Fair values determined by Level 2 inputs use other inputs that are observable, either directly or indirectly.
These Level 2 inputs include quoted prices for similar assets in active markets, quoted prices for identical
or similar assets in markets that are not active, and inputs other than quoted prices that are observable
for the asset.
Level 3
Level 3 inputs are unobservable inputs, including inputs that are available in situations where there is
little, if any, market activity for the related asset.

Note 4 - Fair Value Measurements (Continued)
In instances where inputs used to measure fair value fall into different levels of the fair value hierarchy,
fair value measurements in their entirety are categorized based on the lowest level input that is significant
to the valuation. The Plan’s assessment of the significance of particular inputs to these fair value
measurements requires judgment and considers factors specific to each asset.
The following valuation methodologies have been used to value the Plan's investments:
Short-term Investment Funds
Short-term investment funds consist of interest bearing cash and repurchase agreements that are valued
at their outstanding balances, which approximate fair value due to the short-term maturity of these
investments.
U.S. Government Securities and Municipal Bonds
U.S. government securities and municipal bonds are either valued at the closing price reported in the
active market in which the individual security is traded or valued based on yields currently available on
comparable securities of issuers with similar credit ratings.
Corporate Debt Instruments
The corporate debt instruments are valued using quoted market prices and/or other market data for the
same or comparable instruments and transactions in establishing the prices, discounted cash flow
models, and other pricing models. These models are primarily industry standard models that consider
various assumptions, including time value and yield curve, as well as other relevant economic measures.
Common and Preferred Stocks
Common and preferred stocks are valued at quoted prices reported in active markets.
Registered Investment Companies
Registered investment companies are valued at quoted prices reported in active markets.
Common/Collective Trusts
Common/collective trusts with a readily determinable fair value are valued at net asset value ("NAV"),
which is generally based on the fair value of the funds' underlying net assets and are classified as Level 2
in the accompanying fair value hierarchy. Common/collective trusts without a readily determinable fair
value, because there is no published NAV available, are valued at NAV as a practical expedient and are
not classified within the valuation hierarchy.
Partnerships/Joint Ventures
Investments in private equity, venture capital, and hedge fund partnerships and joint ventures are valued
at NAV per share (or its equivalent) of the funds based on audited financial statements of the funds,
where available, with adjustments to account for partnership activity and other applicable valuation
adjustments.
Other Investments
Other investments consist primarily of future contracts, written and purchased options, swaps and
international government bonds. The futures contracts, written options, purchased options, and swaps
are valued using the last sale price or bid price. The international government bonds are valued at either
the closing price reported on the active market on which the individual securities are traded or valued
based on yields currently available on comparable securities of issuers with similar credit ratings.

Note 5 - Securities Lending
Certain investment managers of the Plan participate in a securities lending program administered by the
Trustee. The transfer of assets under the securities lending program are collateralized with pledges of
collateral. At all times, the borrower must maintain cash or equivalent collateral equal in value to at least
102 percent of the value of the domestic securities loaned and 105 percent of the value of international
securities loaned. Both the collateral and the securities loaned are marked-to-market on a daily basis,
with additional collateral obtained or refunded as necessary. In accordance with accounting standards,
the amount of cash collateral received under securities lending is reported as an asset and a
corresponding payable is recorded on the statements of net assets available for benefits.

Note 6 - Derivative Instruments
The Plan uses derivative instruments to hedge market risk, gain market exposure, and advance the
overall objectives of the Plan and its investment strategies. Derivatives are utilized by external investment
managers retained by the Plan and in protective overlay strategies designed to achieve investment
objectives.
The Plan is party to certain agreements, which are designed to manage exposures to foreign exchange
and interest rate risks. The interest rate and foreign currency instruments are used for the purpose of
hedging changes in the fair value of assets and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits
that result from interest rate changes and currency fluctuations, or as an efficient substitute for traditional
securities. The Plan’s investment policies specifically prohibit the use of derivatives for speculative
purposes.

Note 7 - Plan Termination
Should the Plan terminate at some future time, its net assets generally will not be available on a pro-rata
basis to provide participants’ benefits. Whether a particular participant’s accumulated plan benefits will be
paid depends on both the priority of those benefits and the level of benefits guaranteed by the Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corporation ("PBGC") at that time. Some benefits may be fully or partially provided for
by the then-existing assets and the PBGC guaranty while other benefits may not be provided for at all.
Note 8 - Tax Status
The Plan constitutes a qualified trust under the requirements of Section 401(a) of the IRC and is,
therefore, exempt from federal income taxes under provisions of Section 501(a). The Plan obtained its
latest determination letter on January 25, 2017, in which the Internal Revenue Service ("IRS") stated that
the Plan, as designed, was in compliance with the applicable requirements of the IRC. The Plan has been
amended since receiving the determination letter. However, the Plan’s administrator believes that the
Plan is currently designed and being operated in compliance with the applicable requirements of the IRC.
Therefore, no provision for income taxes has been included in the Plan’s financial statements.
Accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America require plan management to
evaluate tax positions taken by the Plan and recognize a tax liability if the Plan has taken an uncertain
position that more likely than not would not be sustained upon examination by the IRS. The plan
administrator has analyzed the tax positions of the Plan and has concluded that, as of December 31,
2024 and 2023, there are no uncertain position taken or expected to be taken that would require
recognition of a liability and disclosure in the financial statements. The Plan is subject to routine audits by
taxing jurisdictions; however, there are currently no audits for any tax periods in progress.
Note 9 - Related Parties
3M provides certain administrative services to the Plan and does not charge the Plan for these services.
The Trustee and the investment managers are authorized under contract provisions and by ERISA
regulations that provide administrative and statutory exemptions, to invest in funds under their control and
in securities of 3M.
The Plan allows for transactions with certain parties who may perform services or have fiduciary
responsibilities to the Plan, including the Company. At December 31, 2024 and 2023, the Plan held
shares of common stock and/or debt instruments of Bank of New York Mellon.

Note 10 - Purchase of Annuity Contract
During 2024, the Plan purchased an annuity contract from Metropolitan Tower Life Insurance Company
(MetLife). Under the contract, the Plan paid $2,265,104,897 to MetLife, relieving the Plan of any further
benefit obligations for the related retirees and beneficiaries. The Plan transferred approximately
$2,489,000,000 of its defined benefit pension obligations for approximately 23,000 U.S. retirees and
beneficiaries to MetLife. On October 1, 2024, MetLife began paying and administering the retirement
benefits of the retirees and beneficiaries included in this annuity contract purchase. At December 31,
2024, the Plan recorded a receivable in the amount of $31,346,648 related to final participant data
adjustments to the contract. The impact of the annuity contract purchase is not reflected in the
accompanying Statement of Accumulated Plan Benefits as of December 31, 2023.

monthly benefit, beginning when the participant would have

amount to which the participant would have been entitled had

death, survived to Early Retirement, and elected to receive a

attained age 55. For union-free participants, the benefit is
reduced 5% per year for commencement prior to the
participant’s Earliest Unreduced Age. For union participants,
benefits are reduced 5% per year for commencement prior to
age 55.

Special Provisions for Participants Who
Elected Portfolio 2 as of January 1, 2002
Participants as of January 1, 2001 who elected Portfolio 2
benefits have their Portfolio 1 Pension Service frozen as of
January 1, 2002. Their benefit at retirement will be the sum of
their benefit under Portfolio 1 (using Pension Service through
January 1, 2002 but Final Average Pay at termination) and
their benefit under Portfolio 2. Points used to calculate PEP

single-life form, and the benefits paid to date do not exceed

Due to software limitations with the electronic filing process, information filed electronically cannot be

without generating an error. To allow for a successful upload, incorrect entries were made to the electronically
filed Schedule SB. The correct values for these line items are shown in the signed Schedule SB. The values on

and the actual data contained on the signed Schedule SB.
Background
The Solventum Employee Retirement Income Plan (“Solventum ERIP”) was spun off from the 3M Employee
Retirement Income Plan (“3M ERIP”) (EIN/PN: 41-0417775/002) effective April 1, 2024. The valuation
treatment and allocation of results between the two plans was consistent with applicable laws, regulations,
and Gray Book guidance. In particular, 2009 Gray Book Q&A #7 indicates that a new valuation date is not
required as of the spinoff date. Instead, the results as of the beginning of the pre-spinoff plan year (i.e.,
January 1, 2024) were used to allocate the plan year results between the two plans. A new valuation date is
not required as of the spinoff date. Instead, the results as of the beginning of the pre-spinoff plan year (i.e.,
January 1, 2024) were used to allocate the plan year results between the two plans.

Schedule SB, Line 25—Change in Method
The plan sponsor requested Internal Revenue Service (IRS) approval of the funding method change due to the
April 1, 2024 spinoff of the group of participants from the 3M Employee Retirement Income Plan (“3M ERIP”)
that created the Solventum Employee Retirement Income Plan (“Solventum ERIP”) effective April 1, 2024.
The approach to calculating the minimum required contribution reflected in the 2024 Schedule SB is outlined
below:
 The market value of assets and Funding Balances were prorated at January 1, 2024 based on the ratio of
assets as determined by the 4044 valuation results as of April 1, 2024.
 The Value of Plan Assets calculation continues to use the prior two-year smoothing method.
 The Funding Target Liability for benefit accruals were allocated by participant to the Solventum ERIP and
3M ERIP.
 The Target Normal Cost for the 3M ERIP is equal to the sum of:
o The benefits expected to be accrued from January 1, 2024, through December 31, 2024, among the
3M ERIP population, plus
o The benefits expected to be accrued from January 1, 2024, through March 31, 2024, among the
Solventum ERIP population, plus
o The total PBGC premium (which is paid from trust assets) for the 3M EIP before plan spin-off, plus
o Non-PBGC premium administrative expenses expected to be paid from trust assets for the entire plan
from January 1, 2024, through March 31, 2024, plus administrative expenses expected to be paid
from trust assets from April 1, 2024, through December 31, 2024, multiplied by the percentage of
assets allocated to the 3M ERIP. The administrative expenses are assumed to be evenly distributed
throughout the year.
 The pre-2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP is equal to the sum of 3/12ths of the pre-
2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge before the spin-off, plus a portion of the remaining 9/12ths, where
the remaining Shortfall Amortization Charge is allocated between the ongoing 3M ERIP and Solventum
ERIP based on a ratio of the Funding Shortfalls for each plan subsequent to the spin-off as determined
based on the allocation of the Funding Target, Value of Plan Assets, and Prefunding Balances for each
plan.
 The cost of the new 2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP is based on the Funding
Shortfall after the $98,000,000 of prefunding balance was waived. Note that following the spin-off, the
plan sponsor of the Solventum ERIP also waived $227,000,000 of its allocated Prefunding Balance. The
allocation percentages used in allocating the Funding Shortfall Amortization Installments were calculated
before the Solventum ERIP waiver. As a result, the 2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP
would not be affected by the waiver of the Prefunding Balance in the Solventum ERIP.

Background
The Solventum Employee Retirement Income Plan (“Solventum ERIP”) was spun off from the 3M Employee
Retirement Income Plan (“3M ERIP”) (EIN/PN: 41-0417775/002) effective April 1, 2024. The valuation
treatment and allocation of results between the two plans was consistent with applicable laws, regulations,
and Gray Book guidance. In particular, 2009 Gray Book Q&A #7 indicates that a new valuation date is not
required as of the spinoff date. Instead, the results as of the beginning of the pre-spinoff plan year (i.e.,
January 1, 2024) were used to allocate the plan year results between the two plans. A new valuation date is
not required as of the spinoff date. Instead, the results as of the beginning of the pre-spinoff plan year (i.e.,
January 1, 2024) were used to allocate the plan year results between the two plans.

Schedule SB Attachment (Form 5500) —2024 Plan Year
3M Employee Retirement Income Plan
EIN: 41-0417775 PN: 002
Schedule SB, Line 25—Change in Method
The plan sponsor requested Internal Revenue Service (IRS) approval of the funding method change due to the
April 1, 2024 spinoff of the group of participants from the 3M Employee Retirement Income Plan (“3M ERIP”)
that created the Solventum Employee Retirement Income Plan (“Solventum ERIP”) effective April 1, 2024.
The approach to calculating the minimum required contribution reflected in the 2024 Schedule SB is outlined
below:
 The market value of assets and Funding Balances were prorated at January 1, 2024 based on the ratio of
assets as determined by the 4044 valuation results as of April 1, 2024.
 The Value of Plan Assets calculation continues to use the prior two-year smoothing method.
 The Funding Target Liability for benefit accruals were allocated by participant to the Solventum ERIP and
3M ERIP.
 The Target Normal Cost for the 3M ERIP is equal to the sum of:
o The benefits expected to be accrued from January 1, 2024, through December 31, 2024, among the
3M ERIP population, plus
o The benefits expected to be accrued from January 1, 2024, through March 31, 2024, among the
Solventum ERIP population, plus
o The total PBGC premium (which is paid from trust assets) for the 3M EIP before plan spin-off, plus
o Non-PBGC premium administrative expenses expected to be paid from trust assets for the entire plan
from January 1, 2024, through March 31, 2024, plus administrative expenses expected to be paid
from trust assets from April 1, 2024, through December 31, 2024, multiplied by the percentage of
assets allocated to the 3M ERIP. The administrative expenses are assumed to be evenly distributed
throughout the year.
 The pre-2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP is equal to the sum of 3/12ths of the pre-
2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge before the spin-off, plus a portion of the remaining 9/12ths, where
the remaining Shortfall Amortization Charge is allocated between the ongoing 3M ERIP and Solventum
ERIP based on a ratio of the Funding Shortfalls for each plan subsequent to the spin-off as determined
based on the allocation of the Funding Target, Value of Plan Assets, and Prefunding Balances for each
plan.
 The cost of the new 2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP is based on the Funding
Shortfall after the $98,000,000 of prefunding balance was waived. Note that following the spin-off, the
plan sponsor of the Solventum ERIP also waived $227,000,000 of its allocated Prefunding Balance. The
allocation percentages used in allocating the Funding Shortfall Amortization Installments were calculated
before the Solventum ERIP waiver. As a result, the 2024 Shortfall Amortization Charge for the 3M ERIP
would not be affected by the waiver of the Prefunding Balance in the Solventum ERIP.

Schedule SB, line 24—Change in Actuarial Assumptions
The funding valuation reflects the following changes to non-prescribed assumptions:
 The salary increase assumption was changed to better reflect anticipated plan experience.
 The retirement rates for active participants were changed to better reflect anticipated plan
experience.
 The termed vested benefit commencement age assumption was changed to better reflect
anticipated plan experience.
 The termination rates were changed to better reflect anticipated plan experience.
 The percent married assumption was changed to better reflect anticipated plan experience.
 Optional form of benefit payment election percentages were changed to better reflect
anticipated plan experience.
These changes to non-prescribed assumptions were made to better reflect anticipated plan
experience and did not reduce the funding shortfall more than the thresholds stated in Internal
Revenue Code Section 430(h)(5), so approval of the Commissioner is not required.
